21 county; (2) two persons appointed by the governing body of the largest city; (3) two
22 persons appointed by the governing body of the second largest city; and (4) one
23 person who must be a current recipient of assistance from the housing authority
24 appointed by the executive director of the regional housing authority.
25 Existing law sets forth that a housing authority is required to fix the rentals or
26 payments of its housing projects at low rates sufficient for certain purposes and is
27 prohibited from operating for a profit. (NRS 315.500) Section 18 of this bill also
28 authorizes a housing authority to fix the rentals or payments for the purposes of
29 enhancing the ability of the authority to meet its purposes, including providing
30 housing and services for low-income households in the operation area of the
31 authority. Section 18 provides that: (1) certain housing projects constructed or
32 operated that are eligible for low-income housing under certain federal laws are not
33 constructed or operated for a profit; and (2) the provisions do not prohibit
34 authorized actions or impose restrictions on a business entity created by section 5
35 of this bill. Section 18 also exempts a regional housing authority formed pursuant
36 to section 3 from operating for a profit.
37 Existing law requires a housing authority to follow certain conditions when
38 operating or managing a housing project, including renting or leasing a dwelling or
39 accommodation to eligible tenants subject to certain preferences and prohibiting a
40 housing authority from accepting any person as a tenant in a housing project who
41 exceeds certain income limitations. (NRS 315.510) Section 19 of this bill revises
42 the preferences to only include preferences that may be required by the Federal
43 Government pursuant to federal law or in any contract for financial assistance with
44 the authority and eliminates the certain income limitations. Section 19 also clarifies
45 that the provisions do not apply to a business entity created by section 5.
46 Existing law exempts from property taxes the portion of real property that is
47 used for housing and related facilities for persons with low incomes if the portion
48 of the property: (1) qualifies as a low-income unit that is part of a qualified low-
49 income housing project and is financed in part by certain federal or state funding
50 sources; or (2) meets certain affordability requirements set forth in federal law and
51 is financed in part by certain federal funding sources. (NRS 361.082) Existing law
52 requires a housing authority to pay in lieu of taxes to the State or any political
53 subdivision an amount consistent with the maintenance of the low-rent character of
54 the housing project or the achievement of the purposes of the housing authority.
55 (NRS 315.540) Section 20 of this bill provides that a housing authority is exempt
56 from such payments in lieu of taxes if the property meets the requirements for the
57 tax exemption.
58 Existing law defines the terms “veteran” and “serviceman or servicewoman”
59 related to housing authorities. (NRS 315.300) Section 2 of this bill moves and
60 revises the terms “serviceman” and “servicewoman” for the purposes of existing
61 law governing housing authorities. Section 12 of this bill revises the term “veteran”
62 for the purposes of existing law governing housing authorities.
63 Under existing law, a housing authority is authorized to provide, by resolution,
64 compensation for each commissioner of $80 for each meeting attended, but
65 imposes a monthly limit of $240 on such compensation. (NRS 315.390) In lieu of
66 this specified amount of compensation, section 14 of this bill authorizes the
67 housing authority to provide, by resolution, an amount of compensation determined
68 by the housing authority that does not exceed $250 for each meeting attended.
69 Section 14 also eliminates the monthly limit on such compensation.
70 Existing law also creates the Nevada Rural Housing Authority to provide
71 various types of housing services for persons of certain low and moderate income
72 in areas of this State which are not included within the corporate limits of a city or
73 town having a population of 150,000 or more or in other areas pursuant to a
74 contract. (NRS 315.961-315.99874) Existing law: (1) requires the appointment of
75 five persons to serve as commissioners of the Authority; and (2) entitles each
-
